One halfway option in Zig (though I _think_ interfaces are still being considered for addition to the language as first-class citizens) is to use the language&#x27;s metaprogramming facilities.<p>Somebody, once, in the userspace of the language, needs to write a utility that reads a type and produces an interface checker for that type, so that you&#x27;re able to write code like the following:<p><pre><code>  const IDog = Checker(TemplateDogType);
</code></pre>
Then you can use that when defining a function expecting to conform to some interface:<p><pre><code>  fn bark(_dog: anytype) void {
    const dog: IDog(_dog) = _dog;
    dog.bark();
  }
</code></pre>
You can easily get nice compiler errors, no runtime overhead, and all the usual sorts of things you expect from a simple interface system. It&#x27;s just more verbose.<p>Limiting access to non-interface methods without runtime overhead would be a bit more cumbersome I think. Off the top of my head, the following API is possible though:<p><pre><code>  fn bark(dog: anytype) void {
    IDog.bark(&amp;dog);
  }</code></pre>

